# **6. Why does this work?**

The queue always stores **only the latest `size` elements**.

The running `sum` is updated whenever:

* A new element is added.
* An old element is removed.

So, instead of recalculating the sum every time, we simply use:

```text
Average = sum / queue.size()
```

Each element is:

* added once
* removed once

So every operation is efficient.

---

# **7. Java Code**

```java
class MovingAverage {

    Queue<Integer> queue;
    int size;
    double sum;

    public MovingAverage(int size) {
        this.size = size;
        this.queue = new LinkedList<>();
        this.sum = 0;
    }

    public double next(int val) {

        queue.offer(val);
        sum += val;

        if (queue.size() > size) {
            sum -= queue.poll();
        }

        return sum / queue.size();
    }
}
```

---

# **8. Time Complexity**

Each number is:

* inserted once
* removed at most once

Amortized time per `next()`:

```text
O(1)
```

For `n` calls:

```text
O(n)
```

---

# **9. Space Complexity**

The queue stores at most `size` elements.

```text
O(size)
```

---

# **10. Important Interview Note**

This is a classic **Sliding Window** problem implemented using a **Queue**.

Instead of recomputing the sum of the window every time:

* Keep a running `sum`.
* Enqueue the new value.
* Dequeue the oldest value when the window exceeds `size`.
* Compute the average in **O(1)** time.

---

# **11. One-line Note for Interviews**

**Use a Queue to maintain the last `size` numbers and a running `sum`. Add the new value, remove the oldest if the window exceeds `size`, then return `sum / queue.size()`.** üöÄ
